  "onboardingGetStarted": "Get started",
  "onboardingSlide1Title": "Your live GNSS cockpit",
  "onboardingSlide1Body": "Naviscope streams position, altitude, speed, accuracy, and — on supported Android devices — satellite sky plots and signal strength in one instrument-style dashboard.",
  "onboardingSlide2Title": "Sky view & map",
  "onboardingSlide2Body": "Browse constellations, CN0 bars, and a live map. Telemetry stays on your device; nothing is uploaded to our servers.",
  "onboardingSlide3Title": "Location access",
  "onboardingSlide3Body": "Grant location permission when asked. On Android, choose precise location if you want full satellite data. You can change this anytime in system settings.",
  "learnScreenTitle": "GNSS & positioning",
  "learnHubCardTitle": "GNSS & positioning guide",
  "learnHubCardSubtitle": "What GNSS and GPS are, how a fix is computed, accuracy and signals, and how Naviscope maps that to your phone.",
  "learnIntroTitle": "How to read this guide",
  "learnIntroBody": "The sections below are independent topics you can open in any order. They summarize how satellite navigation works at a practical level — useful context when you read live numbers in Naviscope. This is educational material, not a substitute for certified avionics or survey equipment.",
  "learnSec1Title": "What is GNSS?",
  "learnSec1Body": "GNSS means Global Navigation Satellite System: the family of satellite navigation services that broadcast ranging signals from medium Earth orbit (about 20,000 km) toward users on the ground, at sea, and in the air.\n\nEach constellation is operated by a government or agency: the U.S. GPS, European Galileo, Russian GLONASS, Chinese BeiDou, Japanese QZSS, Indian NavIC (IRNSS), plus regional augmentation systems (SBAS) such as WAAS, EGNOS, or MSAS that improve integrity and accuracy over wide areas.\n\nA GNSS receiver does not “connect to the internet” for a basic fix; it listens to radio signals, decodes navigation data, measures ranges to multiple satellites, and solves a positioning equation on your device.",
  "learnSec2Title": "GPS versus GNSS",
  "learnSec2Body": "GPS (officially NAVSTAR GPS) is the United States Space Force–operated constellation. People often say “GPS” when they mean any satellite navigation — technically GPS is only one GNSS.\n\nModern smartphones are multi-GNSS: the chip tracks several constellations at once for more satellites in view, better geometry, and improved availability in urban canyons or under tree cover.\n\nEach satellite transmits on L-band carriers (for example near 1575 MHz for the civil “L1”-class signals). Receivers measure code delay and sometimes carrier phase; Naviscope shows simplified metrics such as CN0 (signal strength) and which satellites are used in the navigation solution where the OS exposes them.",
  "learnSec3Title": "How position is computed",
  "learnSec3Body": "Satellites carry very stable atomic clocks. Each navigation message includes the satellite’s orbit (ephemeris), clock corrections, and time stamps. Your receiver compares the received signal time with its own clock to estimate a pseudorange — a distance plus an unknown clock bias shared across all satellites.\n\nWith four or more good pseudoranges, the receiver can solve for latitude, longitude, altitude, and the clock offset (four unknowns). With fewer satellites you may get a 2D fix (if altitude is assumed) or no fix.\n\nGeometry matters: if all visible satellites sit in one part of the sky, dilution of precision (DOP) is poor and horizontal error grows even with strong signals. Spread satellites lower DOP and usually tighten the fix.",
  "learnSec4Title": "Accuracy, CN0, and “used in fix”",
  "learnSec4Body": "Horizontal accuracy reported by the OS is a statistical uncertainty (often ~68% confidence for Android’s horizontal accuracy field) — not a hard guarantee. It blends signal quality, geometry, multipath, and internal filtering.\n\nCN0 (carrier-to-noise density ratio, in dBHz) describes how strong the signal is relative to noise. Higher CN0 generally means more robust tracking, but a high CN0 alone does not guarantee a small position error if multipath is present.\n\nMultipath happens when reflections (buildings, vehicles, water) make the same satellite arrive from multiple paths; the receiver may lock the wrong delay. Urban canyons worsen both multipath and geometry.\n\n“Used in fix” marks satellites the navigation filter currently weights in the position solution (when the platform exposes this). Manufacturers may differ in how quickly satellites enter or leave that set.",
  "learnSec5Title": "Altitude, speed, and heading",
  "learnSec5Body": "Altitude from GNSS is typically height above a reference ellipsoid (for example WGS84), not necessarily height above mean sea level shown on aviation charts. Geoid separation maps convert between ellipsoid and orthometric heights when you need sea-level-related elevation.\n\nSpeed may come from Doppler on the carrier, from time-differencing consecutive positions, or from fused sensors — different layers on Android and iOS may show slightly different behavior at low speed.\n\nHeading/Course-over-ground is well-defined when you move; when stationary many receivers do not output a meaningful course because direction of travel is undefined. That is why a dashboard may show “—” for heading until you move.",
  "learnSec6Title": "What Naviscope shows on your device",
  "learnSec6Body": "Naviscope reads live location and, on supported Android versions, satellite status from the operating system. The exact fields (accuracy, CN0, azimuth/elevation, used-in-fix) depend on your phone model, Android version, chip firmware, and granted permissions.\n\nOn Android, precise (fine) location permission is typically required for rich satellite telemetry. Approximate-only location may still yield a map position while limiting or disabling detailed GNSS views.\n\nApple’s public iOS APIs expose position, altitude, speed, and course through CoreLocation, but not the same per-satellite sky plot data Android’s GnssStatus API provides. That is a platform policy and API limitation, not something individual apps can bypass.",
  "learnDisclaimer": "Educational summary only. Do not use Naviscope for safety-of-life navigation decisions."
}
